<subSubSection id="C34265476F71FFAAA3C4889DFE8BFDF7" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BE736CC6F71FFAAA3C4889DFE8BFDF7" blockId="38.[151,1436,458,879]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="B92CEADE6F71FFAAA3C4889DFE95FE66" bold="true" box="[199,321,458,483]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Shell small to medium, elongate ovate, moderately thin, and inequivalve; auricles relatively small. Sculpture consisting of 12–16 well defined, low, rounded, primary radial ribs with 1–3 secondary riblets in the interstices. Both ribs and interstices covered in densely imbricated spines, with some spines occasionally being longer, thin and upright. Color variable from uniformly light brown, orange and bright yellow to maculations of orange and white.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34265476F71FFAAA3C48B28FB24FD5B" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BE736CC6F71FFAAA3C48B28FD25FD3F" blockId="38.[151,1436,458,879]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="B92CEADE6F71FFAAA3C48B28FEEFFD12" bold="true" box="[199,315,639,663]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
Since the first report of this species at 
<emphasis id="B92CEADE6F71FFAAA1F38B28FCDEFD13" box="[752,778,639,662]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">EI</emphasis>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC94B3D6F71FFAAA0378B29FC01FD13" author="Raines, B. K." box="[820,981,638,662]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="11 - 40" refId="ref58960" refString="Raines, B. K. (2002) Contributions to the knowledge of Easter Island Mollusca. La Conchiglia, 304, 11 - 40." type="journal article" year="2002">Raines (2002)</bibRefCitation>
, more valves have been collected, so we can now confirm that the species is indeed 
<taxonomicName id="4C584D4F6F71FFAAA17A8BF4FD3EFD3F" authorityName="Lamprell &amp; Healy" authorityYear="2001" box="[633,746,675,699]" class="Bivalvia" family="Spondylidae" genus="Spondylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pectinida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="orstomi">
<emphasis id="B92CEADE6F71FFAAA17A8BF4FD3EFD3F" box="[633,746,675,699]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">S. orstomi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE736CC6F71FFAAA3C48B91FB24FD5B" blockId="38.[151,1436,458,879]" box="[199,1264,710,735]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="B92CEADE6F71FFAAA3C48B91FEFEFD5A" bold="true" box="[199,298,710,735]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" reason="1">Habitat.</emphasis>
Occasionally found at several locations around 
<emphasis id="B92CEADE6F71FFAAA0478B90FC8AFD5B" box="[836,862,711,734]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">EI</emphasis>
, in sand and rubble, from 
<quantity id="4CA09B296F71FFAAA7858B91FB38FD5B" box="[1158,1260,710,734]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="m" value="40.0" valueMax="50.0" valueMin="30.0">30–50 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34265476F71FFAAA3C48BBDFC6BFCEB" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BE736CC6F71FFAAA3C48BBDFC6BFCEB" blockId="38.[151,1436,458,879]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="B92CEADE6F71FFAAA3C48BBDFEB4FC86" bold="true" box="[199,352,746,771]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" reason="1">Distribution.</emphasis>
Although 
<taxonomicName id="4C584D4F6F71FFAAA2D48BBCFD73FC87" authorityName="Lamprell &amp; Healy" authorityYear="2001" box="[471,679,747,771]" class="Bivalvia" family="Spondylidae" genus="Spondylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pectinida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="orstomi">
<emphasis id="B92CEADE6F71FFAAA2D48BBCFD73FC87" box="[471,679,747,771]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Spondylus orstomi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described from 
<collectingCountry id="F34F765C6F71FFAAA7008BBCFB67FC87" box="[1027,1203,746,770]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
, this deep water species has a much wider distribution. It is known from the Coral Sea, 
<collectingCountry id="F34F765C6F71FFAAA0938A59FBC5FCA3" box="[912,1041,782,806]" name="Philippines" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Philippines</collectingCountry>
, and off 
<collectingCountry id="F34F765C6F71FFAAA7708A59FB6DFCA3" box="[1139,1209,782,806]" name="China" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">China</collectingCountry>
. The maximum size currently known is 
<quantity id="4CA09B296F71FFAAA2768A65FE0EFCCF" box="[373,474,818,842]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.06" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="mm" value="60.6">60.6 mm</quantity>
from its furthest range in the East 
<collectingCountry id="F34F765C6F71FFAAA06E8A65FC64FCCF" box="[877,944,818,842]" name="China" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">China</collectingCountry>
Sea (coll. MHU). It has not been recorded from the Hawaiian Islands, 
<collectingCountry id="F34F765C6F71FFAAA2CE8A00FDB7FCEB" box="[461,611,854,878]" name="New Zealand" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
or the Kermadec Islands— 
<emphasis id="B92CEADE6F71FFAAA0948A01FC63FCEA" bold="true" box="[919,951,854,879]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">E4</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
